\section{Modality-specific processing notes}

\subsection{Quantitative structural MRI}

The WAND ses-02 VFA acquisition uses the CUBRIC mcDESPOT protocol: 8
SPGR flip angles (2--18\textdegree, $\text{TR}_\text{exc}$ = 4\,ms)
and 16 bSSFP volumes (8 flip angles $\times$ 2 phase cycles,
$\text{TR}_\text{exc}$ = 4.54\,ms) on the Connectom 3T. The
QMT acquisition comprises 11 MT-weighted volumes at 3 MT flip angles
(332\textdegree, 628\textdegree, 333\textdegree) across offset
frequencies from 1\,kHz to 56\,kHz, plus an MT-off reference.

Four independent fitting tools were applied as test oracles:
QUIT~v3.4~\citep{Wood2018quit} (Ramani + super-Lorentzian, C++),
qMRLab~v2.4.2 (Sled-Pike two-pool, Octave), FreeSurfer
\texttt{mri\_ms\_fitparms} (joint T1/PD), and neurojax (linear
DESPOT1, JAX). The three-way T1 comparison (Table~10) reveals
systematic underestimation (WM 650--727\,ms vs.\ expected $\sim$800\,ms)
consistent with B1$^+$ inhomogeneity, motivating the DESPOT1-HIFI
joint T1+B1 estimation implemented in \texttt{neurojax.qmri.despot}.

The QUIT Ramani QMT model produced physiologically plausible two-pool
parameters (Table~11): BPF WM = 0.121, GM = 0.082 (1.32$\times$);
$T_{1,f}$ WM = 0.87\,s, GM = 1.62\,s; $T_{2,b}$ $\sim$8\,$\mu$s
(super-Lorentzian). Exchange rate instability ($k_{bf}$ upper bound
at some voxels) indicates the need for B1 correction --- a protocol
question for the CUBRIC team (Appendix~\ref{app:cubric}).

\subsection{Perfusion imaging}

WAND ses-03 perfusion data were processed following the ASL white paper
recommendations~\citep{Alsop2015asl}. The pCASL acquisition (bolus =
1.8\,s, PLD = 2.0\,s, 110 volumes) was quantified using FSL
\texttt{oxford\_asl}, which employs the BASIL/FABBER variational
Bayesian inference engine~\citep{Chappell2009basil} for kinetic model
fitting with spatial regularisation. Subject-specific blood T1 was
estimated from the Look-Locker inversion recovery acquisition (128
$\times$ 128, 960 time points, TR = 150\,ms) using the
Deichmann--Haase correction. The fitted value (460\,ms) fell outside
the expected range, defaulting to 1650\,ms --- a fitting issue that
warrants investigation with the CUBRIC team.

TRUST venous oxygenation (24 volumes, TI = 1.02\,s) requires the
protocol-specific effective echo times for accurate T2 $\to$
SvO$_2$ calibration via the Lu et al.\ quadratic
model~\citep{Lu2012bloodt2}. The CUBRIC
\texttt{ep2d\_TRUST\_AsymShTE} protocol uses asymmetric short-TE
encoding; the eTEs are not recorded in the BIDS sidecars and must
be obtained from the sequence documentation.

\subsection{Diffusion microstructure}

DTI fitting was performed on the CHARMED acquisition ($b \leq
1200$\,s/mm$^2$; 83 volumes across $b$ = 0, 200, 500, 1200) without
eddy current correction (topup applied, eddy pending for sub-08033).
The resulting FA and V1 maps were registered to FreeSurfer T1 space
(FLIRT 6-DOF $\to$ \texttt{lta\_convert}) for DTI-enhanced thalamic
nuclei segmentation. Full preprocessing (topup + eddy + bedpostx +
probtrackx2 + connectome) is planned for the DGX.

The WAND AxCaliber data (4 shells, $b$ = 0--15500\,s/mm$^2$, 264
volumes on 300\,mT/m gradients) will be processed with sbi4dwi for
axon diameter estimation and microstructure-informed connectome
construction via the \texttt{ConnectomeMapper}.

\subsection{Magnetic resonance spectroscopy}
\label{app:mrs}

\paragraph{Acquisition parameters.}
ses-04 semi-LASER at 7\,T: TE = 78\,ms, TR = 5230\,ms, 64 averages,
BW = 3000\,Hz, 2048 points. Four VOI placements: anterior cingulate
cortex (25$\times$30$\times$40\,mm$^3$), occipital
(30$\times$30$\times$30\,mm$^3$), right auditory
(30$\times$45$\times$20\,mm$^3$), left sensorimotor
(30$\times$30$\times$30\,mm$^3$). VAPOR water suppression.

ses-05 MEGA-PRESS at 3\,T: TE = 68\,ms, TR = 2000\,ms, 160 averages,
BW = 2000\,Hz, 2048 points. Same four VOI placements. Editing pulses
at 1.9\,ppm (ON) and 7.5\,ppm (OFF), bandwidth 100\,Hz.

\paragraph{Processing pipeline.}
Raw Siemens TWIX data were read with \texttt{pymapVBVD} (bypassing a
\texttt{spec2nii} validation bug on numeric PatientName fields in the
TWIX header). Coil combination used sensitivity weighting with phase
alignment to coil~0. MEGA-PRESS ON/OFF subtraction was performed
after coil combination. All data were converted to NIfTI-MRS format
using the \texttt{nifti\_mrs} Python library with monkey-patched
header validation.

\paragraph{Basis set considerations.}
Initial fitting used singlet basis spectra (delta-function FIDs at
known chemical shifts) with FSL-MRS Newton fitting, yielding GABA
CRLB = 19.4\% and GPC CRLB = 12.4\% for the occipital VOI. NAA
and Glu showed poor CRLBs ($>$100\%) because singlet approximations
do not capture J-coupling evolution at TE = 78\,ms. Proper J-coupled
basis spectra are required.

Three sources of validated basis spectra are available:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{MRSHub}\footnote{\url{https://mrshub.org/datasets_basissets/}}:
    community repository of downloadable basis sets for various
    sequences and field strengths.
  \item \textbf{LCModel}\footnote{\url{https://www.lcmodel.com/lcm-basis.shtml}}:
    pre-computed basis sets for 7\,T (and other field strengths).
  \item \textbf{VESPA/PyGAMMA}\footnote{\url{https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10330446/}}:
    density matrix simulation using PyGAMMA (v4.3.4, built locally)
    with sequence-specific pulse definitions. Generates basis spectra
    accounting for J-coupling evolution under the exact sLASER/MEGA-PRESS
    timing.
\end{itemize}

The impact of using ideal hard pulses versus realistic adiabatic RF
shapes in semi-LASER basis simulation has been characterised by
Landheer et al.~\citep{Landheer2021slaser}, who showed that shaped
pulses and magnetic field gradients can significantly affect basis
spectra for strongly coupled spin systems at short TE, though the
effect diminishes at longer TE. The across-vendor standardisation of
semi-LASER~\citep{Oz2020slaser} provides the reference pulse
definitions (GOIA-WURST, GOIA-HS) used in Siemens implementations.

\paragraph{Metabolite quantification at 7\,T.}
Approximately 18 metabolites are quantifiable at 7\,T using
semi-LASER~\citep{Tkac2009sevenT}, including GABA ($\sim$1--2\,mM in
GM), glutamate ($\sim$8--12\,mM), glutamine ($\sim$3--5\,mM), NAA
($\sim$8--12\,mM), and myo-inositol ($\sim$5--8\,mM). The 3-fold
reduction in Cram\'{e}r-Rao lower bounds at 7\,T versus
3\,T~\citep{Mekle2009sevenT} is critical for resolving GABA without
editing, providing cross-validation against the ses-05 MEGA-PRESS
GABA estimate.

\paragraph{Multiway spectral analysis.}
The raw MRS data tensor (spectral $\times$ coils $\times$ averages)
is amenable to chemometrics-inspired decomposition methods
implemented in \texttt{neurojax.qmri.mrs\_tensor}: Tucker/HOSVD for
optimal coil combination, PARAFAC for component separation, and
MCR-ALS for data-driven spectral unmixing without pre-defined basis
sets. These connect to the established multiway analysis literature
in analytical chemistry~\citep{Bro1997parafac} and provide an
alternative to basis-set-dependent fitting.

\subsection{MEG electrophysiology}

ses-01 MEG data (CTF 275-channel, 1200\,Hz, 5 paradigms) will be
processed with the osl-ephys pipeline~\citep{vanEs2025oslephys}:
ICA-based artefact rejection, RHINO coregistration to FreeSurfer
surfaces, beamformer/minimum-norm source reconstruction, parcellation
to Desikan-Killiany atlas, and sign-flipping across subjects.
Source-level timeseries feed into osl-dynamics for HMM/DyNeMo brain
state analysis~\citep{Gohil2023dynemo}: time-delay embedding + PCA
preparation, state spectral decomposition, and summary statistics
(fractional occupancy, lifetime, switching rate).

\subsection{TMS-EEG}

ses-08 SICI (short-interval intracortical inhibition) data were
acquired with a Magstim BiStim$^2$ (D70 Alpha Flat coil,
BrainSight neuronavigation, Polaris optical tracking). Three runs
per subject provide test-pulse and conditioned-pulse TMS-evoked
potentials (TEPs) for extraction of the N15, P30, N45, P60, N100,
P180 components. TEP waveforms and global field power serve as
fitting targets for the whole-brain neural mass model.

\section{CUBRIC protocol questions}
\label{app:cubric}

The following questions have been compiled during processing and are
pending responses from the CUBRIC team:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item QMT MT pulse duration (Trf) for the \texttt{tfl\_qMT\_v09}
    sequence.
  \item B1$^+$ map availability for ses-02 (critical for QMT and VFA
    T1 accuracy).
  \item TRUST effective echo times for the
    \texttt{ep2d\_TRUST\_AsymShTE} protocol.
  \item SPGR flip angle ordering in the 4D VFA file (assumed
    2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 18\textdegree).
  \item SSFP flip angles and phase cycling scheme (8 FAs $\times$ 2
    phase cycles assumed).
  \item sLASER RF pulse waveform files for basis set simulation.
  \item MEGA-PRESS editing pulse shape and timing details.
  \item Cross-session registration validation (Connectom $\to$ Prisma
    geometric distortion).
  \item Pre-computed basis spectra for sLASER at 7\,T and MEGA-PRESS
    at 3\,T (if available).
\end{enumerate}

The full list of 26 questions is maintained in
\texttt{docs/CUBRIC\_QUESTIONS.md} in the repository.

